('Complex brain networks: graph theoretical analysis of structural and functional systems', 'Ed Bullmore, Olaf Sporns', '2009', 'Recent developments in the quantitative analysis of complex networks, based largely on graph theory, have been rapidly translated to studies of brain network organization. The brain''s structural and functional systems have features of complex networks -- such as small-world topology, highly connected hubs and modularity -- both at the whole-brain scale of human neuroimaging and at a cellular scale in non-human animals. In this article, we review studies investigating complex brain network topolo', 'https://www.nature.com/articles/nrn2575', '14965', 'Google Scholar / Nature Reviews Neuroscience', 'Google Scholar / Nature Reviews Neuroscience', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('A default mode of brain function', 'Marcus E. Raichle, Abraham M. MacLeod, Abraham Z. Snyder, William J. Powers, Debra A. Gusnard, Gordon L. Shulman', '2001', 'A baseline or default state of brain activity has been hypothesized to exist in the human brain. This default mode is characterized by a consistent decrease in activity during goal-directed, attention-demanding tasks compared to a passive resting state. We propose that this default mode represents an organized, baseline state of brain function that is suspended during specific goal-directed behaviors.', 'https://www.pnas.org/doi/abs/10.1073/pnas.98.2.676', '16337', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('Complex network measures of brain connectivity: uses and interpretations', 'Mikail Rubinov, Olaf Sporns', '2010', 'Brain connectivity datasets comprise networks of brain regions connected by anatomical tracts or by functional associations. Complex network analysis aims to characterize these brain networks with a small number of neurobiologically meaningful and easily computable measures. This article discusses construction of brain networks from connectivity data and describes the most commonly used network measures of structural and functional connectivity, including measures that detect functional integrat', 'https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Complex-network-measures-of-brain-connectivity%3A-and-Rubinov-Sporns/9cd87eb83bc93161b226731116ec105c0a9c7cb5', '13934', 'Semantic Scholar / NeuroImage', 'Semantic Scholar / NeuroImage', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('Mapping the structural core of human cerebral cortex', 'Patric Hagmann, Leila Cammoun, Xavier Gigandet, Reto Meuli, Christopher J. Honey, Van J. Wedeen, Olaf Sporns', '2008', 'Structurally segregated and functionally specialized regions of the human cerebral cortex are interconnected by a dense network of cortico-cortical axonal pathways. Using diffusion spectrum imaging, we noninvasively mapped these pathways within and across cortical hemispheres in individual human participants. An analysis of the resulting large-scale structural brain networks reveals a structural core within posterior medial and parietal cerebral cortex, as well as several distinct temporal and f', 'https://journals.plos.org/plosbiology/article?id=10.1371/journal.pbio.0060159', '5358', 'Semantic Scholar / PLoS Biology', 'Semantic Scholar / PLoS Biology', 'Self-Attention', datetime('now')),
('The human connectome: a structural description of the human brain', 'Olaf Sporns, Giulio Tononi, Rolf Kotter', '2005', 'To understand the functioning of a network, one must know its elements and their interconnections. The purpose of this article is to discuss research strategies aimed at a comprehensive structural description of the network of elements and connections forming the human brain. We propose to call this dataset the human ''connectome,'' and we argue that it is fundamentally important in cognitive neuroscience and neuropsychology. The connectome will significantly increase our understanding of how func', 'https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.0010042', '4427', 'Google Scholar / PLoS Computational Biology', 'Google Scholar / PLoS Computational Biology', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('The economy of brain network organization', 'Ed Bullmore, Olaf Sporns', '2012', 'The brain is expensive, incurring high material and metabolic costs for its size. Many aspects of brain network organization can be mostly explained by a parsimonious drive to minimize these costs. However, brain networks also have high topological efficiency, robustness, modularity and a ''rich club'' of connector hubs. We propose that brain organization is shaped by an economic trade-off between minimizing costs and allowing the emergence of adaptively valuable topological patterns of anatomical', 'https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22498897/', '4214', 'PubMed / Nature Reviews Neuroscience', 'PubMed / Nature Reviews Neuroscience', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('Predicting human resting-state functional connectivity from structural connectivity', 'Christopher J. Honey, Olaf Sporns, Leila Cammoun, Xavier Gigandet, Jean-Philippe Thiran, Reto Meuli, Patric Hagmann', '2009', 'Structurally connected brain regions tend to show correlated spontaneous neural activity in the absence of an explicit task, a phenomenon known as resting-state functional connectivity. We investigated the relationship between structural connectivity and resting-state functional connectivity in healthy human participants. We found that functional connectivity was significantly correlated with structural connectivity, but the relationship was complex and nonlinear.', 'https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.0811168106', '4013', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Self-Attention', datetime('now')),
('Dynamic functional connectivity: promise, issues, and interpretations', 'R. Matthew Hutchison, Thilo Womelsdorf, Elena A. Allen, Peter A. Bandettini, Vince D. Calhoun, Maurizio Corbetta, Sandra E. Della Penna, Jeff H. Duyn, Gary H. Glover, Javier Gonzalez-Castillo, Daniel A. Handwerker, Sheila Keilholz, Vesa Kiviniemi, David A. Leopold, Francesco de Pasquale, Olaf Sporns, Martin Walter, Catie Chang', '2013', 'The time-varying nature of functional connectivity has emerged as an important consideration in studies of brain network organization. This article reviews the growing body of literature on dynamic functional connectivity, examining the promise of this approach while also addressing methodological issues and interpretational challenges. We discuss the potential importance of time-varying connectivity for understanding brain function and its alterations in disease.', 'https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23707587/', '3575', 'PubMed / NeuroImage', 'PubMed / NeuroImage', 'Self-Attention', datetime('now')),
('Network neuroscience', 'Danielle S. Bassett, Olaf Sporns', '2017', 'Network neuroscience describes the use of network science and graph theory to study the structure and function of complex neural systems. The brain can be understood as a network at multiple scales, from neurons to circuits to large-scale systems. Network approaches have revealed fundamental organizational principles of brain networks, including small-world topology, rich-club organization, and modular architecture, and have provided insights into brain development, function, and disease.', 'https://www.nature.com/articles/nn.4502', '3415', 'Google Scholar / Nature Neuroscience', 'Google Scholar / Nature Neuroscience', 'Self-Attention', datetime('now')),
('Networks of the Brain', 'Olaf Sporns', '2011', 'In Networks of the Brain, Olaf Sporns describes how the integrative nature of brain function can be illuminated from a complex network perspective. The book synthesizes current knowledge about brain network organization across scales, from neurons to large-scale brain systems, and discusses how network approaches can help understand brain function, development, disease, and evolution. It covers fundamental concepts in network science and their application to neuroscience.', 'https://mitpress.mit.edu/9780262014694/networks-of-the-brain/', '3282', 'Google Scholar / MIT Press', 'Google Scholar / MIT Press', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('Rich-club organization of the human connectome', 'Martijn P. van den Heuvel, Olaf Sporns', '2011', 'The human brain is a complex network of interlinked regions. Recent studies have demonstrated the existence of a number of highly connected and highly central neocortical hub regions. This study maps out both the subcortical and neocortical hubs of the brain and demonstrates that brain hubs form a so-called ''rich club,'' characterized by a tendency for high-degree nodes to be more densely connected among themselves than nodes of a lower degree, providing important information on the higher-level ', 'https://www.jneurosci.org/content/31/44/15775', '2843', 'PubMed / Journal of Neuroscience', 'PubMed / Journal of Neuroscience', 'Self-Attention', datetime('now')),
('Organization, development and function of complex brain networks', 'Olaf Sporns, Dante R. Chialvo, Markus Kaiser, Claus C. Hilgetag', '2004', 'Recent research has revealed general principles in the structural and functional organization of complex networks which are shared by various natural, social and technological systems. This review examines these principles as applied to the organization, development and function of complex brain networks. We examine the structural properties of large-scale anatomical and functional brain networks and discuss how they might arise in the course of network growth and rewiring.', 'https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15350243/', '2776', 'PubMed / Trends in Cognitive Sciences', 'PubMed / Trends in Cognitive Sciences', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('Network hubs in the human brain', 'Martijn P. van den Heuvel, Olaf Sporns', '2013', 'Network hubs are brain regions that occupy highly central positions in the brain''s network architecture. Hubs play a crucial role in integrative brain function by linking diverse functional modules and facilitating efficient information flow. This review discusses the identification of network hubs, their structural and functional characteristics, their role in brain development and disease, and their evolutionary significance.', 'https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24231140/', '2586', 'PubMed / Trends in Cognitive Sciences', 'PubMed / Trends in Cognitive Sciences', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('A measure for brain complexity: relating functional segregation and integration in the nervous system', 'Giulio Tononi, Olaf Sporns, Gerald M. Edelman', '1994', 'Understanding the function of the nervous system requires a comprehensive analysis of how the brain integrates information across specialized regions while maintaining functional segregation. We propose a measure for brain complexity that captures the interplay between functional segregation and integration. This measure, called neural complexity, reflects the degree to which a neural system can simultaneously exhibit both specialized (segregated) and unified (integrated) patterns of activity.', 'https://www.pnas.org/doi/abs/10.1073/pnas.91.11.5033', '2252', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('Network structure of cerebral cortex shapes functional connectivity on multiple time scales', 'Christopher J. Honey, Rolf Kotter, Michael Breakspear, Olaf Sporns', '2007', 'Cortical circuits are composed of neurons that are recurrently connected through a complex pattern of synaptic connections. These circuits are embedded within a larger network of cortical areas that are interconnected through long-range projections. We investigated how the structure of cortical networks shapes functional connectivity at multiple temporal scales, finding that network architecture fundamentally constrains the patterns of correlated neural activity observed at different frequencies', 'https://www.pnas.org/doi/abs/10.1073/pnas.0701519104', '2130', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Time Series', datetime('now')),
('Emerging concepts for the dynamical organization of resting-state activity in the brain', 'Gustavo Deco, Viktor K. Jirsa, Anthony R. McIntosh', '2011', 'A broad body of experimental work has demonstrated that apparently spontaneous brain activity is not random. At the level of large-scale neural systems, as measured with fMRI, this ongoing activity reflects the organization of a series of highly coherent functional networks. These so-called resting-state networks closely relate to the underlying anatomical connectivity but cannot be understood in those terms alone. We review three large-scale neural system models that emphasize the key contribut', 'https://www.nature.com/articles/nrn2961', '2157', 'PubMed / Nature Reviews Neuroscience', 'PubMed / Nature Reviews Neuroscience', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now')),
('The human brain is intrinsically organized into dynamic, anticorrelated functional networks', 'Michael D. Fox, Abraham Z. Snyder, Justin L. Vincent, Maurizio Corbetta, David C. Van Essen, Marcus E. Raichle', '2005', 'Many functional brain imaging studies have reported the existence of brain regions that decrease their activity during attention-demanding cognitive tasks, a phenomenon known as task-induced deactivation. We demonstrate that these regions are not simply deactivated but are instead organized into a coherent, functionally connected network that is anticorrelated with a task-positive network. The anticorrelated relationship between these networks suggests that the brain is intrinsically organized i', 'https://www.pnas.org/doi/abs/10.1073/pnas.0504136102', '8211', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Google Scholar / PNAS', 'Medical Imaging', datetime('now'));